This code in NUnitEqualityComparer is intended to cause your implementation of IEquatable to be used:

```
        if (FirstImplementsIEquatableOfSecond(xType, yType))
            return InvokeFirstIEquatableEqualsSecond(expected, actual);
        else if (FirstImplementsIEquatableOfSecond(yType, xType))
            return InvokeFirstIEquatableEqualsSecond(actual, expected);
```

We know it works in simple cases, where the objects directly implement the interface but I'm not sure if it is handling the situation you have, where there are three levels of interface inheritance. It may simply be that we are not finding the interfaces. It would help if you could narrow down a minimal test case for us to work on.

Of course, this will be fixed in NUnit 3.0, so we'll have to retest it in that environment.

Here are a few tests that illustrate the issue. Let me know if this isn't quite what you're getting at.
- A class that only implements `IEquatable<>` passes the test
- A class that implements `IEquatable<>` plus at least one more interface fails the test when compared using `NUnitEqualityComparer`
- A class that implements `IEquatable<>` plus at least one more interface passes when compared using `Enumerable.SequenceEqual<>`.

``` C#
    using System;
    using System.Collections.Generic;
    using System.Linq;
    using NUnit.Framework;
    using NUnit.Framework.Constraints;

    namespace NUnit_Bug
    {
        public class Object1 : IEquatable<Object1>
        {
            public int SomeProperty { get; set; }
            public bool Equals(Object1 other)
            {
                if (other == null)
                {
                    return false;
                }
                return SomeProperty == other.SomeProperty;
            }
        }

        public interface IObject2 : IEquatable<IObject2>
        {
            int SomeProperty { get; set; }
        }

        public class Object2 : IObject2
        {
            public int SomeProperty { get; set; }

            public bool Equals(IObject2 other) {
                if (other == null)
                {
                    return false;
                }
                return SomeProperty == other.SomeProperty;
            }
        }

        [TestFixture]
        public class Tests
        {
            [Test]
            public void EnumerablesWithSingleInterface_WithEqualContents_AreEqual() {
                var listA = new List<Object1>
                {
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                var listB = new List<Object1>
                {
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object1 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                var n = new NUnitEqualityComparer();
                var tolerance = Tolerance.Zero;
                var actualResult = n.AreEqual(listA, listB,ref tolerance);
                Assert.IsTrue(actualResult);
            }

            [Test]
            public void EnumerablesWithTwoInterfaces_WithEqualContents_AreEqualUsingNUnit()
            {
                var listA = new List<IObject2>
                {
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                var listB = new List<IObject2>
                {
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                var n = new NUnitEqualityComparer();
                var tolerance = Tolerance.Zero;
                var actualResult = n.AreEqual(listA, listB, ref tolerance);
                Assert.IsTrue(actualResult);
            }

            [Test]
            public void EnumerablesWithTwoInterfaces_WithEqualContents_AreEqualUsingLinq()
            {
                var listA = new List<IObject2>
                {
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                var listB = new List<IObject2>
                {
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 1},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 2},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 3},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 4},
                    new Object2 {SomeProperty = 5},
                };

                Assert.IsTrue(listA.SequenceEqual(listB));
            }
        }
    }
```

Thanks, this will be helpful in fixing the bug. AFAICS the problem is in
how NUnit is detecting the fact that the interface is implemented... we
need to recurse.

The fact that Assert.IsTrue() passes isn't really relevant... it naturally
passes whenever its argument is true.

Charlie

